This is my remembrance of the days leading up to the bin Laden raid, the day of the raid centered on the iconic Situation Room photograph, and the day after.⁣
⁣
Note that the most important people from this day are not pictured at all. Our country owes a debt of gratitude to Admiral Bill McRaven, the former Commander of Special Operations, and the members of SEAL Team Six that planned for and executed the mission. They are the real heroes of this day. It was a real honor to be at Fort Campbell a few days later when they presented President Obama with the American flag that flew aboard the helicopter.⁣
⁣
If you have more questions, please leave them in the comments section. I will try to answer the ones that I can. I will not be able to respond to questions about what was on the screen during the raid or what I might have overheard.⁣
⁣
Please stay safe, practice social distancing, and wear a mask when you’re out and about!⁣
⁣
⁣
⁣
⁣

Two weeks ago, I had the chance to discuss some of my photographs with Michael Shaw and Cara Finnegan of Chatting the Pictures. The program is produced by the visual and media literacy organization, Reading the Pictures. Here is the last part of the program looking at presidential leadership in a health crisis. We discussed one of my contact sheets from President Reagan’s visit to the National Institute of Health. The appearance took place during the AIDS epidemic on July 23, 1987, and it featured Reagan holding a baby that had the virus. 
Follow @readingthepictures on Instagram.

In this photo, taken October 10, 2011, President Obama walks into a hospital room at Walter Reed National Military Medical Center in Bethesda, Md., where he presented a wounded warrior with a Purple Heart.⁣
⁣
The program is produced by the visual and media literacy non-profit, Reading the Pictures. ⁣

node.text:
Crossing Afghanistan’s Hindu Kush mountains in November 2001.⁣
⁣
Getting into Kabul, Afghanistan, as the war began proved challenging. This was before U.S. troops were on the ground but as air strikes were taking place. ⁣
⁣
The border from Pakistan was closed. So we flew first to Moscow, and then after receiving a visa, onto Tajikistan. It took another week to get a visa to enter northern Afghanistan. ⁣
⁣
We spent a couple of weeks there, which at the time was a part of the country not controlled by the Taliban. ⁣
⁣
Then colleague Paul Salopek and I, along with our 21-year-old interpreter, made an arduous three day drive to the Anjuman Pass where we crossed over the Hindu Kush at 14,500 feet. ⁣
⁣
We survived that night only because we came across a small Northern Alliance hut outfitted with a wood burning stove.⁣ We slept on the floor with a dozen or so fighters. 
⁣
The next day, we were able to get a car ride to the outskirts of Kabul.⁣
⁣

node.text:
Kabul, Afghanistan, November 2001⁣
⁣
A Pashtun girl weeps as her family packs up to flee Kabul after the Northern Alliance had taken over the city from the Taliban.⁣
⁣
This photograph accompanied a story by my colleague Paul Salopek. These paragraphs are particularly prescient in retrospect with what’s happening today.⁣
⁣
“Bad memories between ethnic groups run deep in Afghanistan, far beyond the current civil war, which pits minority Uzbeks and Tajiks from the north--and, in some cases, Sunni Muslims called Hazaras from the west--against the mainly Pashtun Taliban.⁣
⁣
For centuries, outside powers have used this crippling divisiveness to carve out influence in the region, easily pitting Afghan against Afghan.⁣
⁣
But the most recent--and worst--case of ethnic rivalry can be pinned on the Afghans themselves.⁣
⁣
When the Soviet army pulled out of Kabul in 1989, after a failed invasion that cost 15,000 Soviet lives, Afghanistan's ethnically based political groups tore each other to pieces. Today, about half of Kabul looks like a stand-in for Stalingrad after World War II, an apocalyptic cityscape of smashed factories, scrapped tanks and pulverized apartment blocks. Between 30,000 and 100,000 Kabul residents died in such brutal internecine battles.”

Today would have been my mom’s 95th birthday. ⁣
⁣
As a long-time nurse, I’m sure she would have had a lot to say about our current situation. ⁣
⁣
Certainly she would be happy to know that her friend Joe Biden was the President.⁣
⁣
We’re hoping to have a proper memorial service for her this fall, which we haven’t been able to do because of covid. ⁣
⁣
Happy Birthday mom! ⁣
⁣

Almost 20 years ago, I covered the fall of Kabul, Afghanistan, as the Northern Alliance fighters first gathered outside of the capital city before entering triumphantly. ⁣
⁣
They were, of course, backed in the preceding weeks by relentless U.S. air strikes which caused the Taliban to relinquish control. ⁣
⁣
Watching the news today with memories of my time in Afghanistan in late 2001.⁣
⁣
⁣
⁣
⁣

node.text:
Happy 60th birthday to my friend, former President Barack Obama.⁣
⁣
Remembering your first birthday at the White House where you celebrated with your family and the staff with a medley of pies made by the WH pastry chefs. ⁣
⁣
And then you stopped by the Brady Press Briefing Room to wish a Happy Birthday to Helen Thomas, the dean of the WH press corps, who shared the same birthday with you. ⁣
⁣

Last year, my daughter made this picture of me standing in front of this beautiful mural that was created by DAMA (Dane Arts Mural Arts) in Madison as part of the State Street mural project.⁣
⁣
I’m sad to report that the depiction of President Obama was vandalized beyond repair, and the city had to paint over his portrait (swipe to see how it looks today).⁣
⁣
To support the Madison Arts Commission, I made a donation to the Friends of the Madison Arts Commission (www.friendsofmadisonarts.org). Direct link in profile for DAMA (daneartsmuralarts.org). Let’s hope they are able to re-do the mural of President Obama, so he can be pictured once again next to Michelle.⁣
⁣
⁣
